,0.0096729,0.03679728,0.19061637,-0.01671848,0.02124677,0.00851862,-0.04936346,-0.01527353,0.0017233,-0.01676146,-0.01216054,0.04837424,0.12340148,-0.07656712,0.04782962,0.08034117,-0.08561104,-0.06067885,-0.00195329,-0.03417555,0.06159404,0.05309935,-0.05445703,-0.03431587,0.09979323,-0.06325735,-0.02918166,-0.04435493,-0.04119225,0.04793464,0.02043858,0.01036774,0.0103741,0.02395104,-0.00428991,-0.04532132,-0.03836518,-0.00231753,-0.01741362,-0.06200461,-0.05296037,-0.0359391,-0.05011588,0.16407414,0.00584457],"last_embed":{"hash":"1wnhu8l","tokens":471}}},"last_read":{"hash":"1wnhu8l","at":1774951895281},"class_name":"SmartSource","last_import":{"mtime":1774951828294,"size":2133,"at":1774951884828,"hash":"1wnhu8l"},"blocks":{"#---frontmatter---":[1,33],"#Neurobiological effects of the green tea constituent theanine and its potential role in the treatment of psychiatric and neurodegenerative disorders":[35,39],"#Neurobiological effects of the green tea constituent theanine and its potential role in the treatment of psychiatric and neurodegenerative disorders#{1}":[37,39]},"outlinks":[{"title":"Author/Anne L. Lardner","target":"Author/Anne L. Lardner","line":27},{"title":"Author/Anne L. Lardner","target":"Author/Anne L. Lardner","line":28},{"title":"PDF","target":"biblib/lardner_neurobiological_2014/lardner_neurobiological_2014.pdf","line":30}],"metadata":{"id":"lardner_neurobiological_2014","type":"article-journal","title":"Neurobiological effects of the green tea constituent theanine and its potential role in the treatment of psychiatric and neurodegenerative disorders","issued":{"date-parts":[[2014]]},"DOI":"10.1179/1476830513y.0000000079","container-title":"Nutritional Neuroscience","abstract":"AbstractTheanine (n-ethylglutamic acid), a non-proteinaceous amino acid component of green and black teas, has received growing attention in recent years due to its reported effects on the central nervous system. It readily crosses the blood–brain barrier where it exerts a variety of neurophysiological and pharmacological effects. Its most well-documented effect has been its apparent anxiolytic and calming effect due to its up-regulation of inhibitory neurotransmitters and possible modulation of serotonin and dopamine in selected areas. It has also recently been shown to increase levels of brain-derived neurotrophic factor. An increasing number of studies demonstrate a neuroprotective effects following cerebral infarct and injury, although the exact molecular mechanisms remain to be fully elucidated. Theanine also elicits improvements in cognitive function including learning and memory, in human and animal studies, possibly via a decrease in NMDA-dependent CA1 long-term potentiation (LTP) and increase in ...","tags":["#literature_note"],"author":[{"family":"Lardner","given":"Anne L.","literal":""},{"family":"Lardner","given":"Anne L.","literal":""}],"citation-key":"lardner_neurobiological_2014","year":"2014","dateCreated":"2026-03-31","reading-status":"to-read","aliases":["Neurobiological effects of the green tea constituent theanine and its potential role in the treatment of psychiatric and neurodegenerative disorders"],"author-links":["[[Author/Anne L. Lardner]]","[[Author/Anne L. Lardner]]"],"attachment":["[[biblib/lardner_neurobiological_2014/lardner_neurobiological_2014.pdf|PDF]]"],"related":[[]]},"task_lines":[],"tasks":{},"codeblock_ranges":[],"last_embed":{"hash":"1wnhu8l","at":1774951895271}},"smart_blocks:Research/@lardner_neurobiological_2014.md#---frontmatter---": {"path":null,"embeddings":{"TaylorAI/bge-micro-v2":{"vec":[0.0266735,-0.00274529,0.01042084,0.03426245,-0.02127903,0.02562967,0.06506624,0.0429002,-0.02087875,-0.00336624,0.00529581,-0.05781848,0.03326529,0.09932824,0.00207252,-0.00233811,-0.0259023,0.01785011,-0.05181703,-0.02774588,-0.03014754,-0.07889938,0.08475056,-0.02797381,-0.01601014,0.00393062,-0.07356639,0.01026466,-0.09171753,-0.24273656,0.00775035,0.02633272,0.04023517,-0.06274876,-0.06889047,0.011